hands_on_practices.problem:
Let $L$ be a first-order language and let $T$ be a set of $L$-sentences. Let $\varphi$ be an $L$-sentence. Recall that a set $\Sigma$ of $L$-sentences is satisfiable if there exists a structure (a model) $\mathcal{M}$ for $L$ such that $\mathcal{M} \models \Sigma$, and unsatisfiable otherwise. The Compactness Theorem for First-Order Logic (FOL) asserts that a set $\Sigma$ of $L$-sentences is satisfiable if and only if every finite subset of $\Sigma$ is satisfiable. Suppose $T \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is unsatisfiable. Which of the following arguments correctly and rigorously shows, using only the Compactness Theorem, that there exists a finite subset $T_0 \subseteq T$ such that $T_0 \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is unsatisfiable?

A. Since $T \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is unsatisfiable, by the contrapositive of the Compactness Theorem, there exists a finite $\Sigma_0 \subseteq T \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ that is unsatisfiable. Let $T_0 := \Sigma_0 \cap T$. Then either $\Sigma_0 = T_0$ or $\Sigma_0 = T_0 \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$. In the first case, $T_0$ is already unsatisfiable, hence $T_0 \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is unsatisfiable. In the second case, $\Sigma_0 = T_0 \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is unsatisfiable by construction. Thus, in all cases, there is a finite $T_0 \subseteq T$ with $T_0 \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ unsatisfiable.

B. Since $T \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is unsatisfiable, we have $T \models \varphi$. By the Completeness Theorem, $T \vdash \varphi$. Any formal proof is finite, so only finitely many premises from $T$ are used; call them $T_0$. Then $T_0 \vdash \varphi$, hence $T_0 \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is inconsistent and thus unsatisfiable. Therefore, there exists a finite $T_0 \subseteq T$ with $T_0 \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ unsatisfiable.

C. By the Compactness Theorem, if $T \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is unsatisfiable then every finite subset of $T \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is unsatisfiable. Hence, in particular, for any finite $T_0 \subseteq T$, the set $T_0 \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is unsatisfiable.

D. By the Compactness Theorem, there is a model $\mathcal{M} \models T$ such that $\mathcal{M} \models \varphi$. Therefore, taking $T_0 := \varnothing$ yields $T_0 \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ unsatisfiable since $
eg \varphi$ contradicts $\varphi$ in $\mathcal{M}$.

E. By the Compactness Theorem, if $T \models \varphi$ then there exists a finite $T_0 \subseteq T$ such that $T_0 \models \varphi$. Since $T \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is unsatisfiable, we have $T \models \varphi$, thus such a finite $T_0$ exists and $T_0 \cup \{
eg \varphi\}$ is unsatisfiable.
